    <subfield code="a">Louisa M. Sewall paid her pledge to Mrs. Mirriam the day after she made it, while attending the convention in the afternoon that &quot;Miss [Abby] Kelly and Dr. Manford spoke.&quot; Louisa M. Sewall&apos;s &quot;aunt Southwick&quot; (Mrs. Thankful Hussey Southwick?) found a five dollar bill on the floor and thinks that it may belong to Mrs. Maria Weston Chapman. Louisa M. Sewall wants to resign as secretary (of the Boston Female Anti-Slavery Society?). Louisa M. Sewall was delighted with Maria W. Chapman&apos;s review of Charles Simmon&apos;s sermons. (Scripture Manual, by Charles Simmons.)</subfield>
